title: As Debt Default Looms, Yellen Faces Her Biggest Test Yet
content: The Treasury secretary must wade into a standoff between Democrats and Republicans over raising the debt limit.

title: Uncertainty Swirls Around Evergrande as a Payment Deadline Passes
content: A payment on China Evergrande’s dollar-denominated bonds was due Thursday. By the end of the business day in New York, the company had still not said publicly whether it made the payment or planned to.

title: An Experiment to Stop Online Abuse Falls Short in Germany
content: Despite having one of the world’s toughest laws against online hate speech and harassment, Germany has struggled to contain toxic content ahead of its Sept. 26 election.

title: News Media Can’t Shake ‘Missing White Woman Syndrome,’ Critics Say
content: Major outlets have highlighted the case of Gabrielle Petito while often ignoring stories about women of color who go missing.

title: In Push to Tax the Rich, White House Spotlights Billionaires’ Tax Rates
content: A White House analysis using an unconventional methodology says the wealthiest Americans pay far less in taxes than others.

title: Rural America’s Roads Might Resemble Cuba in 20 Years
content: As the nation shifts to electric vehicles, picture well-kept but long discontinued gas-powered pickups, especially in areas where charging stations may be sparse.

title: Residents of Troubled Supertall Tower Seek $125 Million in Damages
content: The condo board at 432 Park Avenue is suing the developers for construction and design defects that have led to floods, faulty elevators, and electrical explosions.

title: Federal Reserve Signals a Shift Away From Pandemic Support
content: The Fed said it could soon slow its large-scale purchases of government-backed bonds and indicated it might raise interest rates in 2022.

title: Beyond Evergrande’s Troubles, a Slowing Chinese Economy
content: Investors are watching whether the property developer defaults. But in the background, the world’s No. 2 economy is flashing numerous warning signs.

title: An Insider Details the ‘Black Box’ of Money and Power in China
content: A memoir by a well-connected businessman offers insights into the Communist Party’s thinking as it tightens its grip on the private sector.

title: Federal Panel Recommends Booster Shots, Opening New Campaign Against the Virus
content: Scientific advisers to the C.D.C. endorsed additional doses of the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for older Americans but not for health care workers, in a possible rift with regulators.

title: Delta urges airlines to create a national ‘no fly’ list of problematic passengers.
content: The carrier informed flight attendants about its request ahead of a House hearing on increased unruliness on flights.

title: Catalan Separatist Leader, Carles Puigdemont, Is Arrested in Italy
content: The arrest of Mr. Puigdemont, on the island of Sardinia, came on a warrant issued by Spain’s Supreme Court on charges of sedition.

title: 3 Million Baby Cushions Are Recalled After 8 Reported Infant Deaths
content: The Boppy Company lounger pads, which federal regulators say can cause suffocation, were sold by retailers including Pottery Barn Kids, Walmart, Target and Amazon.

title: A record number of cargo ships off the California coast shows a crack in the supply chain.
content: Sixty-one vessels were anchored offshore on Thursday waiting to unload cargo at the Port of Los Angeles and the Port of Long Beach, down from 73 on Sunday.

title: Biden’s Pick for Bank Regulator Worries Banks Are Getting Too Powerful
content: Saule Omarova, a Cornell law professor, has advocated a more equal share of power and success between taxpayers and big banks.

title: New Director for Mass MoCA
content: Kristy Edmunds is to replace the museum’s longtime leader, Joseph C. Thompson, in October.

title: Turkey’s currency hits a new low after a surprise interest rate cut.
content: The country’s central bank lowered the interest rate to 18 percent, below the annual rate of inflation, which was 19.3 percent in August.

title: A ‘Race-Free’ Approach to Diagnosing Kidney Disease
content: The most common method of assessing the condition may make Black patients seem less ill than they really are, some experts say. A new report calls for scrapping the formula.

title: Mo Abudu Isn’t Waiting for Permission
content: Known as “Africa’s answer to Oprah,” Abudu has built a media empire aimed at bringing Nigerian stories to the world. Her huge Netflix deal should help.

title: Regulators Racing Toward First Major Rules on Cryptocurrency
content: Concerned about the potential for a digital-era bank run, the Treasury Department is working on an oversight framework for the fast-growing sector.

title: Is the Seller’s Market Over?
content: Slowing sales, a decline in over-asking contract prices, and fewer bidding wars in many areas are among recent shifts.

title: Who’s Buying Evergrande?
content: As fears of the fallout from the Chinese property developer’s potential collapse fade, some investors see an opportunity.

title: In a setback for Apple, the European Union seeks a common charger for all phones.
content: The push to make USB-C connectors standard on all mobile devices would primarily affect Apple, which uses proprietary technology for charging.

title: Business groups are divided as China seeks self-reliance.
content: European companies warned on Thursday that China’s push to replace imports was harmful, but American companies are more eager to cooperate with Beijing.

title: Wikipedia’s next leader on preventing misinformation: ‘Neutrality requires understanding.’
content: The online encyclopedia is often cited as a place that, on balance, helps combat false and misleading information.

title: California governor signs bill that could push Amazon to change labor practices.
content: “The hardworking warehouse employees who have helped sustain us during these unprecedented times should not have to risk injury or face punishment,” Gov. Gavin Newsom said.

title: Biden Huddles With Democrats as Divisions Threaten His Agenda
content: Democrats are nearing a make-or-break moment for President Biden’s agenda, with party divisions imperiling top-priority legislation and fiscal crises looming.

title: At Covid Summit, Biden Sets Ambitious Goals for Vaccinating the World
content: But his plans face a tough road as pressure grows for big pharmaceutical companies to share their vaccine technologies with poorer nations.

title: F.D.A. Authorizes Pfizer Booster Shots for Older and At-Risk Americans
content: Regulators said that people over 65 or at high risk of severe Covid-19 were eligible for an extra shot, setting up a staggered national booster campaign.

title: The U.S. Is Lifting Travel Restrictions for Visitors. What Do the New Rules Mean?
content: The Biden administration will allow vaccinated international travelers to enter the United States, including those from previously banned countries. Details remain to be worked out, but here is what we know so far.

title: Facebook’s Chief Technology Officer to Step Down in 2022
content: Mike Schroepfer, who leads the company’s artificial intelligence and other technical efforts, said he planned to transition into a role as a senior fellow.
